As I have been out, and find your boy waiting, I will keep the orthographical curiosity,<note>Presumably a letter that Lemon thought comic in its spelling, sent to amuse CD.</note> to read while you read this. I went to Forster<note>John Forster (1812-76; <hi rend="italic">Dictionary of National Biography</hi>), historian and man of letters, CD's closest friend and biographer.</note> this morning, who is willing.<note>Possibly echoing Barkis in <hi rend="italic">David Copperfield</hi>, No. II, Ch. V; not yet published but the No. completed by 5 May. The proposal was a trip to the Derby, 23 May; the party consisted of CD, Lemon, Leech, and, replacing Forster, John Gordon (see Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 5, p. 414n); CD’s servant, John Thompson, probably also went.</note> We three should be too much for a barouche<note>“A four-wheeled carriage with a half-head behind which can be raised or let down at pleasure, having a seat in front for the driver, and seats inside for two couples to sit facing each other” (<hi rend="italic">Oxford English Dictionary</hi>).</note> – I mean, we four. But do you think there is any other kind of conveyance – and pair, say – that would be at once comfortable and spicey?<note>“Full of spirit, smartness, or ‘go’” (<hi rend="italic">Oxford English Dictionary</hi>), with particular reference to horses or horse-drawn vehicles.</note> I fear not – but think of it. And if your thinking should come to anything, let me know tomorrow.
